     102                 :            :    vectype according to the type of the result (lhs).  For stmts whose
     103                 :            :    result-type is different than the type of the arguments (e.g., demotion,

    1640                 :            : 
    1641                 :            : /* Function vect_enhance_data_refs_alignment
    1642                 :            : 
    1643                 :            :    This pass will use loop versioning and loop peeling in order to enhance
    1644                 :            :    the alignment of data references in the loop.
    1645                 :            : 
    1646                 :            :    FOR NOW: we assume that whatever versioning/peeling takes place, only the
    1647                 :            :    original loop is to be vectorized.  Any other loops that are created by
    1648                 :            :    the transformations performed in this pass - are not supposed to be
    1649                 :            :    vectorized.  This restriction will be relaxed.
    1650                 :            : 
    1651                 :            :    This pass will require a cost model to guide it whether to apply peeling
    1652                 :            :    or versioning or a combination of the two.  For example, the scheme that
    1653                 :            :    intel uses when given a loop with several memory accesses, is as follows:
    1654                 :            :    choose one memory access ('p') which alignment you want to force by doing
    1655                 :            :    peeling.  Then, either (1) generate a loop in which 'p' is aligned and all
    1656                 :            :    other accesses are not necessarily aligned, or (2) use loop versioning to
    1657                 :            :    generate one loop in which all accesses are aligned, and another loop in
    1658                 :            :    which only 'p' is necessarily aligned.
    1659                 :            : 
    1660                 :            :    ("Automatic Intra-Register Vectorization for the Intel Architecture",
    1661                 :            :    Aart J.C. Bik, Milind Girkar, Paul M. Grey and Ximmin Tian, International
    1662                 :            :    Journal of Parallel Programming, Vol. 30, No. 2, April 2002.)
    1663                 :            : 
    1664                 :            :    Devising a cost model is the most critical aspect of this work.  It will
    1665                 :            :    guide us on which access to peel for, whether to use loop versioning, how
    1666                 :            :    many versions to create, etc.  The cost model will probably consist of
    1667                 :            :    generic considerations as well as target specific considerations (on
    1668                 :            :    powerpc for example, misaligned stores are more painful than misaligned
    1669                 :            :    loads).
    1670                 :            : 
    1671                 :            :    Here are the general steps involved in alignment enhancements:
    1672                 :            : 
    1673                 :            :      -- original loop, before alignment analysis:
    1674                 :            :         for (i=0; i<N; i++){
    1675                 :            :           x = q[i];                     # DR_MISALIGNMENT(q) = unknown
    1676                 :            :           p[i] = y;                     # DR_MISALIGNMENT(p) = unknown
    1677                 :            :         }
    1678                 :            : 
    1679                 :            :      -- After vect_compute_data_refs_alignment:
    1680                 :            :         for (i=0; i<N; i++){
    1681                 :            :           x = q[i];                     # DR_MISALIGNMENT(q) = 3
    1682                 :            :           p[i] = y;                     # DR_MISALIGNMENT(p) = unknown
    1683                 :            :         }
    1684                 :            : 
    1685                 :            :      -- Possibility 1: we do loop versioning:
    1686                 :            :      if (p is aligned) {
    1687                 :            :         for (i=0; i<N; i++){ # loop 1A
    1688                 :            :           x = q[i];                     # DR_MISALIGNMENT(q) = 3
    1689                 :            :           p[i] = y;                     # DR_MISALIGNMENT(p) = 0
    1690                 :            :         }
    1691                 :            :      }
    1692                 :            :      else {
    1693                 :            :         for (i=0; i<N; i++){ # loop 1B
    1694                 :            :           x = q[i];                     # DR_MISALIGNMENT(q) = 3
    1695                 :            :           p[i] = y;                     # DR_MISALIGNMENT(p) = unaligned
    1696                 :            :         }
    1697                 :            :      }
    1698                 :            : 
    1699                 :            :      -- Possibility 2: we do loop peeling:
    1700                 :            :      for (i = 0; i < 3; i++){        # (scalar loop, not to be vectorized).
    1701                 :            :         x = q[i];
    1702                 :            :         p[i] = y;
    1703                 :            :      }
    1704                 :            :      for (i = 3; i < N; i++){        # loop 2A
    1705                 :            :         x = q[i];                       # DR_MISALIGNMENT(q) = 0
    1706                 :            :         p[i] = y;                       # DR_MISALIGNMENT(p) = unknown
    1707                 :            :      }
    1708                 :            : 
    1709                 :            :      -- Possibility 3: combination of loop peeling and versioning:
    1710                 :            :      for (i = 0; i < 3; i++){        # (scalar loop, not to be vectorized).
    1711                 :            :         x = q[i];
    1712                 :            :         p[i] = y;
    1713                 :            :      }
    1714                 :            :      if (p is aligned) {
    1715                 :            :         for (i = 3; i<N; i++){       # loop 3A
    1716                 :            :           x = q[i];                     # DR_MISALIGNMENT(q) = 0
    1717                 :            :           p[i] = y;                     # DR_MISALIGNMENT(p) = 0
    1718                 :            :         }
    1719                 :            :      }
    1720                 :            :      else {
    1721                 :            :         for (i = 3; i<N; i++){       # loop 3B
    1722                 :            :           x = q[i];                     # DR_MISALIGNMENT(q) = 0
    1723                 :            :           p[i] = y;                     # DR_MISALIGNMENT(p) = unaligned
    1724                 :            :         }
    1725                 :            :      }
    1726                 :            : 
    1727                 :            :      These loops are later passed to loop_transform to be vectorized.  The
    1728                 :            :      vectorizer will use the alignment information to guide the transformation
    1729                 :            :      (whether to generate regular loads/stores, or with special handling for
    1730                 :            :      misalignment).  */
    1731                 :            :

    4605                 :            : /* Function vect_create_addr_base_for_vector_ref.
    4606                 :            : 
    4607                 :            :    Create an expression that computes the address of the first memory location
    4608                 :            :    that will be accessed for a data reference.
    4609                 :            :

    4611                 :            :    STMT_INFO: The statement containing the data reference.

    4613                 :            :    OFFSET: Optional. If supplied, it is be added to the initial address.
    4614                 :            :    LOOP:    Specify relative to which loop-nest should the address be computed.
    4615                 :            :             For example, when the dataref is in an inner-loop nested in an
    4616                 :            :             outer-loop that is now being vectorized, LOOP can be either the
    4617                 :            :             outer-loop, or the inner-loop.  The first memory location accessed
    4618                 :            :             by the following dataref ('in' points to short):
    4619                 :            : 
    4620                 :            :                 for (i=0; i<N; i++)
    4621                 :            :                    for (j=0; j<M; j++)
    4622                 :            :                      s += in[i+j]

    4624                 :            :             is as follows:
    4625                 :            :             if LOOP=i_loop:     &in         (relative to i_loop)
    4626                 :            :             if LOOP=j_loop:     &in+i*2B    (relative to j_loop)
    4627                 :            :    BYTE_OFFSET: Optional, defaulted to NULL.  If supplied, it is added to the
    4628                 :            :             initial address.  Unlike OFFSET, which is number of elements to
    4629                 :            :             be added, BYTE_OFFSET is measured in bytes.
    4630                 :            : 
    4631                 :            :    Output:
    4632                 :            :    1. Return an SSA_NAME whose value is the address of the memory location of
    4633                 :            :       the first vector of the data reference.
    4634                 :            :    2. If new_stmt_list is not NULL_TREE after return then the caller must insert
    4635                 :            :       these statement(s) which define the returned SSA_NAME.
    4636                 :            : 
    4637                 :            :    FORNOW: We are only handling array accesses with step 1.  */

    4719                 :            : /* Function vect_create_data_ref_ptr.
    4720                 :            : 
    4721                 :            :    Create a new pointer-to-AGGR_TYPE variable (ap), that points to the first
    4722                 :            :    location accessed in the loop by STMT_INFO, along with the def-use update
    4723                 :            :    chain to appropriately advance the pointer through the loop iterations.
    4724                 :            :    Also set aliasing information for the pointer.  This pointer is used by
    4725                 :            :    the callers to this function to create a memory reference expression for
    4726                 :            :    vector load/store access.
    4727                 :            : 
    4728                 :            :    Input:
    4729                 :            :    1. STMT_INFO: a stmt that references memory. Expected to be of the form
    4730                 :            :          GIMPLE_ASSIGN <name, data-ref> or
    4731                 :            :          GIMPLE_ASSIGN <data-ref, name>.
    4732                 :            :    2. AGGR_TYPE: the type of the reference, which should be either a vector
    4733                 :            :         or an array.
    4734                 :            :    3. AT_LOOP: the loop where the vector memref is to be created.
    4735                 :            :    4. OFFSET (optional): an offset to be added to the initial address accessed
    4736                 :            :         by the data-ref in STMT_INFO.
    4737                 :            :    5. BSI: location where the new stmts are to be placed if there is no loop
    4738                 :            :    6. ONLY_INIT: indicate if ap is to be updated in the loop, or remain
    4739                 :            :         pointing to the initial address.
    4740                 :            :    7. BYTE_OFFSET (optional, defaults to NULL): a byte offset to be added
    4741                 :            :         to the initial address accessed by the data-ref in STMT_INFO.  This is
    4742                 :            :         similar to OFFSET, but OFFSET is counted in elements, while BYTE_OFFSET
    4743                 :            :         in bytes.
    4744                 :            :    8. IV_STEP (optional, defaults to NULL): the amount that should be added
    4745                 :            :         to the IV during each iteration of the loop.  NULL says to move
    4746                 :            :         by one copy of AGGR_TYPE up or down, depending on the step of the

    4751                 :            :       data reference (initial addressed accessed by the data reference).

    4753                 :            : 
    4754                 :            :       v8hi *ap;
    4755                 :            :       ap = (v8hi *)initial_address;

    4758                 :            :          initial_address = &a[init];

    5275                 :            : /* Function vect_permute_store_chain.
    5276                 :            : 
    5277                 :            :    Given a chain of interleaved stores in DR_CHAIN of LENGTH that must be
    5278                 :            :    a power of 2 or equal to 3, generate interleave_high/low stmts to reorder
    5279                 :            :    the data correctly for the stores.  Return the final references for stores
    5280                 :            :    in RESULT_CHAIN.
    5281                 :            : 
    5282                 :            :    E.g., LENGTH is 4 and the scalar type is short, i.e., VF is 8.
    5283                 :            :    The input is 4 vectors each containing 8 elements.  We assign a number to
    5284                 :            :    each element, the input sequence is:
    5285                 :            : 
    5286                 :            :    1st vec:   0  1  2  3  4  5  6  7
    5287                 :            :    2nd vec:   8  9 10 11 12 13 14 15
    5288                 :            :    3rd vec:  16 17 18 19 20 21 22 23
    5289                 :            :    4th vec:  24 25 26 27 28 29 30 31
    5290                 :            : 
    5291                 :            :    The output sequence should be:
    5292                 :            : 
    5293                 :            :    1st vec:  0  8 16 24  1  9 17 25
    5294                 :            :    2nd vec:  2 10 18 26  3 11 19 27
    5295                 :            :    3rd vec:  4 12 20 28  5 13 21 30
    5296                 :            :    4th vec:  6 14 22 30  7 15 23 31
    5297                 :            : 
    5298                 :            :    i.e., we interleave the contents of the four vectors in their order.
    5299                 :            : 
    5300                 :            :    We use interleave_high/low instructions to create such output.  The input of
    5301                 :            :    each interleave_high/low operation is two vectors:
    5302                 :            :    1st vec    2nd vec
    5303                 :            :    0 1 2 3    4 5 6 7
    5304                 :            :    the even elements of the result vector are obtained left-to-right from the
    5305                 :            :    high/low elements of the first vector.  The odd elements of the result are
    5306                 :            :    obtained left-to-right from the high/low elements of the second vector.
    5307                 :            :    The output of interleave_high will be:   0 4 1 5
    5308                 :            :    and of interleave_low:                   2 6 3 7
    5309                 :            : 
    5310                 :            : 
    5311                 :            :    The permutation is done in log LENGTH stages.  In each stage interleave_high
    5312                 :            :    and interleave_low stmts are created for each pair of vectors in DR_CHAIN,
    5313                 :            :    where the first argument is taken from the first half of DR_CHAIN and the
    5314                 :            :    second argument from it's second half.
    5315                 :            :    In our example,
    5316                 :            : 
    5317                 :            :    I1: interleave_high (1st vec, 3rd vec)
    5318                 :            :    I2: interleave_low (1st vec, 3rd vec)
    5319                 :            :    I3: interleave_high (2nd vec, 4th vec)
    5320                 :            :    I4: interleave_low (2nd vec, 4th vec)
    5321                 :            : 
    5322                 :            :    The output for the first stage is:
    5323                 :            : 
    5324                 :            :    I1:  0 16  1 17  2 18  3 19
    5325                 :            :    I2:  4 20  5 21  6 22  7 23
    5326                 :            :    I3:  8 24  9 25 10 26 11 27
    5327                 :            :    I4: 12 28 13 29 14 30 15 31
    5328                 :            : 
    5329                 :            :    The output of the second stage, i.e. the final result is:
    5330                 :            : 
    5331                 :            :    I1:  0  8 16 24  1  9 17 25
    5332                 :            :    I2:  2 10 18 26  3 11 19 27
    5333                 :            :    I3:  4 12 20 28  5 13 21 30
    5334                 :            :    I4:  6 14 22 30  7 15 23 31.  */

    5473                 :            : /* Function vect_setup_realignment
    5474                 :            : 
    5475                 :            :    This function is called when vectorizing an unaligned load using
    5476                 :            :    the dr_explicit_realign[_optimized] scheme.
    5477                 :            :    This function generates the following code at the loop prolog:
    5478                 :            : 
    5479                 :            :       p = initial_addr;
    5480                 :            :    x  msq_init = *(floor(p));   # prolog load
    5481                 :            :       realignment_token = call target_builtin;
    5482                 :            :     loop:
    5483                 :            :    x  msq = phi (msq_init, ---)
    5484                 :            : 
    5485                 :            :    The stmts marked with x are generated only for the case of
    5486                 :            :    dr_explicit_realign_optimized.
    5487                 :            : 
    5488                 :            :    The code above sets up a new (vector) pointer, pointing to the first
    5489                 :            :    location accessed by STMT_INFO, and a "floor-aligned" load using that
    5490                 :            :    pointer.  It also generates code to compute the "realignment-token"
    5491                 :            :    (if the relevant target hook was defined), and creates a phi-node at the
    5492                 :            :    loop-header bb whose arguments are the result of the prolog-load (created
    5493                 :            :    by this function) and the result of a load that takes place in the loop
    5494                 :            :    (to be created by the caller to this function).
    5495                 :            : 
    5496                 :            :    For the case of dr_explicit_realign_optimized:
    5497                 :            :    The caller to this function uses the phi-result (msq) to create the
    5498                 :            :    realignment code inside the loop, and sets up the missing phi argument,
    5499                 :            :    as follows:
    5500                 :            :     loop:
    5501                 :            :       msq = phi (msq_init, lsq)
    5502                 :            :       lsq = *(floor(p'));        # load in loop
    5503                 :            :       result = realign_load (msq, lsq, realignment_token);
    5504                 :            : 
    5505                 :            :    For the case of dr_explicit_realign:
    5506                 :            :     loop:
    5507                 :            :       msq = *(floor(p));        # load in loop
    5508                 :            :       p' = p + (VS-1);
    5509                 :            :       lsq = *(floor(p'));       # load in loop
    5510                 :            :       result = realign_load (msq, lsq, realignment_token);
    5511                 :            : 
    5512                 :            :    Input:
    5513                 :            :    STMT_INFO - (scalar) load stmt to be vectorized. This load accesses
    5514                 :            :                a memory location that may be unaligned.
    5515                 :            :    BSI - place where new code is to be inserted.
    5516                 :            :    ALIGNMENT_SUPPORT_SCHEME - which of the two misalignment handling schemes
    5517                 :            :                               is used.

    5883                 :            : /* Function vect_permute_load_chain.
    5884                 :            : 
    5885                 :            :    Given a chain of interleaved loads in DR_CHAIN of LENGTH that must be
    5886                 :            :    a power of 2 or equal to 3, generate extract_even/odd stmts to reorder
    5887                 :            :    the input data correctly.  Return the final references for loads in
    5888                 :            :    RESULT_CHAIN.
    5889                 :            : 
    5890                 :            :    E.g., LENGTH is 4 and the scalar type is short, i.e., VF is 8.
    5891                 :            :    The input is 4 vectors each containing 8 elements. We assign a number to each
    5892                 :            :    element, the input sequence is:
    5893                 :            : 
    5894                 :            :    1st vec:   0  1  2  3  4  5  6  7
    5895                 :            :    2nd vec:   8  9 10 11 12 13 14 15
    5896                 :            :    3rd vec:  16 17 18 19 20 21 22 23
    5897                 :            :    4th vec:  24 25 26 27 28 29 30 31
    5898                 :            : 
    5899                 :            :    The output sequence should be:
    5900                 :            : 
    5901                 :            :    1st vec:  0 4  8 12 16 20 24 28
    5902                 :            :    2nd vec:  1 5  9 13 17 21 25 29
    5903                 :            :    3rd vec:  2 6 10 14 18 22 26 30
    5904                 :            :    4th vec:  3 7 11 15 19 23 27 31
    5905                 :            : 
    5906                 :            :    i.e., the first output vector should contain the first elements of each
    5907                 :            :    interleaving group, etc.
    5908                 :            : 
    5909                 :            :    We use extract_even/odd instructions to create such output.  The input of
    5910                 :            :    each extract_even/odd operation is two vectors
    5911                 :            :    1st vec    2nd vec
    5912                 :            :    0 1 2 3    4 5 6 7
    5913                 :            : 
    5914                 :            :    and the output is the vector of extracted even/odd elements.  The output of
    5915                 :            :    extract_even will be:   0 2 4 6
    5916                 :            :    and of extract_odd:     1 3 5 7
    5917                 :            : 
    5918                 :            : 
    5919                 :            :    The permutation is done in log LENGTH stages.  In each stage extract_even
    5920                 :            :    and extract_odd stmts are created for each pair of vectors in DR_CHAIN in
    5921                 :            :    their order.  In our example,
    5922                 :            : 
    5923                 :            :    E1: extract_even (1st vec, 2nd vec)
    5924                 :            :    E2: extract_odd (1st vec, 2nd vec)
    5925                 :            :    E3: extract_even (3rd vec, 4th vec)
    5926                 :            :    E4: extract_odd (3rd vec, 4th vec)
    5927                 :            : 
    5928                 :            :    The output for the first stage will be:
    5929                 :            : 
    5930                 :            :    E1:  0  2  4  6  8 10 12 14
    5931                 :            :    E2:  1  3  5  7  9 11 13 15
    5932                 :            :    E3: 16 18 20 22 24 26 28 30
    5933                 :            :    E4: 17 19 21 23 25 27 29 31
    5934                 :            : 
    5935                 :            :    In order to proceed and create the correct sequence for the next stage (or
    5936                 :            :    for the correct output, if the second stage is the last one, as in our
    5937                 :            :    example), we first put the output of extract_even operation and then the
    5938                 :            :    output of extract_odd in RESULT_CHAIN (which is then copied to DR_CHAIN).
    5939                 :            :    The input for the second stage is:
    5940                 :            : 
    5941                 :            :    1st vec (E1):  0  2  4  6  8 10 12 14
    5942                 :            :    2nd vec (E3): 16 18 20 22 24 26 28 30
    5943                 :            :    3rd vec (E2):  1  3  5  7  9 11 13 15
    5944                 :            :    4th vec (E4): 17 19 21 23 25 27 29 31
    5945                 :            : 
    5946                 :            :    The output of the second stage:
    5947                 :            : 
    5948                 :            :    E1: 0 4  8 12 16 20 24 28
    5949                 :            :    E2: 2 6 10 14 18 22 26 30
    5950                 :            :    E3: 1 5  9 13 17 21 25 29
    5951                 :            :    E4: 3 7 11 15 19 23 27 31
    5952                 :            : 
    5953                 :            :    And RESULT_CHAIN after reordering:
    5954                 :            : 
    5955                 :            :    1st vec (E1):  0 4  8 12 16 20 24 28
    5956                 :            :    2nd vec (E3):  1 5  9 13 17 21 25 29
    5957                 :            :    3rd vec (E2):  2 6 10 14 18 22 26 30
    5958                 :            :    4th vec (E4):  3 7 11 15 19 23 27 31.  */

    6076                 :            : /* Function vect_shift_permute_load_chain.
    6077                 :            : 
    6078                 :            :    Given a chain of loads in DR_CHAIN of LENGTH 2 or 3, generate
    6079                 :            :    sequence of stmts to reorder the input data accordingly.
    6080                 :            :    Return the final references for loads in RESULT_CHAIN.
    6081                 :            :    Return true if successed, false otherwise.
    6082                 :            : 
    6083                 :            :    E.g., LENGTH is 3 and the scalar type is short, i.e., VF is 8.
    6084                 :            :    The input is 3 vectors each containing 8 elements.  We assign a
    6085                 :            :    number to each element, the input sequence is:
    6086                 :            : 
    6087                 :            :    1st vec:   0  1  2  3  4  5  6  7
    6088                 :            :    2nd vec:   8  9 10 11 12 13 14 15
    6089                 :            :    3rd vec:  16 17 18 19 20 21 22 23
    6090                 :            : 
    6091                 :            :    The output sequence should be:
    6092                 :            : 
    6093                 :            :    1st vec:  0 3 6  9 12 15 18 21
    6094                 :            :    2nd vec:  1 4 7 10 13 16 19 22
    6095                 :            :    3rd vec:  2 5 8 11 14 17 20 23
    6096                 :            : 
    6097                 :            :    We use 3 shuffle instructions and 3 * 3 - 1 shifts to create such output.
    6098                 :            : 
    6099                 :            :    First we shuffle all 3 vectors to get correct elements order:
    6100                 :            : 
    6101                 :            :    1st vec:  ( 0  3  6) ( 1  4  7) ( 2  5)
    6102                 :            :    2nd vec:  ( 8 11 14) ( 9 12 15) (10 13)
    6103                 :            :    3rd vec:  (16 19 22) (17 20 23) (18 21)
    6104                 :            : 
    6105                 :            :    Next we unite and shift vector 3 times:
    6106                 :            : 
    6107                 :            :    1st step:
    6108                 :            :      shift right by 6 the concatenation of:
    6109                 :            :      "1st vec" and  "2nd vec"
    6110                 :            :        ( 0  3  6) ( 1  4  7) |( 2  5) _ ( 8 11 14) ( 9 12 15)| (10 13)
    6111                 :            :      "2nd vec" and  "3rd vec"
    6112                 :            :        ( 8 11 14) ( 9 12 15) |(10 13) _ (16 19 22) (17 20 23)| (18 21)
    6113                 :            :      "3rd vec" and  "1st vec"
    6114                 :            :        (16 19 22) (17 20 23) |(18 21) _ ( 0  3  6) ( 1  4  7)| ( 2  5)
    6115                 :            :                              | New vectors                   |
    6116                 :            : 
    6117                 :            :      So that now new vectors are:
    6118                 :            : 
    6119                 :            :      1st vec:  ( 2  5) ( 8 11 14) ( 9 12 15)
    6120                 :            :      2nd vec:  (10 13) (16 19 22) (17 20 23)
    6121                 :            :      3rd vec:  (18 21) ( 0  3  6) ( 1  4  7)
    6122                 :            : 
    6123                 :            :    2nd step:
    6124                 :            :      shift right by 5 the concatenation of:
    6125                 :            :      "1st vec" and  "3rd vec"
    6126                 :            :        ( 2  5) ( 8 11 14) |( 9 12 15) _ (18 21) ( 0  3  6)| ( 1  4  7)
    6127                 :            :      "2nd vec" and  "1st vec"
    6128                 :            :        (10 13) (16 19 22) |(17 20 23) _ ( 2  5) ( 8 11 14)| ( 9 12 15)
    6129                 :            :      "3rd vec" and  "2nd vec"
    6130                 :            :        (18 21) ( 0  3  6) |( 1  4  7) _ (10 13) (16 19 22)| (17 20 23)
    6131                 :            :                           | New vectors                   |
    6132                 :            : 
    6133                 :            :      So that now new vectors are:
    6134                 :            : 
    6135                 :            :      1st vec:  ( 9 12 15) (18 21) ( 0  3  6)
    6136                 :            :      2nd vec:  (17 20 23) ( 2  5) ( 8 11 14)
    6137                 :            :      3rd vec:  ( 1  4  7) (10 13) (16 19 22) READY
    6138                 :            : 
    6139                 :            :    3rd step:
    6140                 :            :      shift right by 5 the concatenation of:
    6141                 :            :      "1st vec" and  "1st vec"
    6142                 :            :        ( 9 12 15) (18 21) |( 0  3  6) _ ( 9 12 15) (18 21)| ( 0  3  6)
    6143                 :            :      shift right by 3 the concatenation of:
    6144                 :            :      "2nd vec" and  "2nd vec"
    6145                 :            :                (17 20 23) |( 2  5) ( 8 11 14) _ (17 20 23)| ( 2  5) ( 8 11 14)
    6146                 :            :                           | New vectors                   |
    6147                 :            : 
    6148                 :            :      So that now all vectors are READY:
    6149                 :            :      1st vec:  ( 0  3  6) ( 9 12 15) (18 21)
    6150                 :            :      2nd vec:  ( 2  5) ( 8 11 14) (17 20 23)
    6151                 :            :      3rd vec:  ( 1  4  7) (10 13) (16 19 22)
    6152                 :            : 
    6153                 :            :    This algorithm is faster than one in vect_permute_load_chain if:
    6154                 :            :      1.  "shift of a concatination" is faster than general permutation.
    6155                 :            :          This is usually so.
    6156                 :            :      2.  The TARGET machine can't execute vector instructions in parallel.
    6157                 :            :          This is because each step of the algorithm depends on previous.
    6158                 :            :          The algorithm in vect_permute_load_chain is much more parallel.
    6159                 :            : 
    6160                 :            :    The algorithm is applicable only for LOAD CHAIN LENGTH less than VF.
    6161                 :            : */

    6569                 :            :   /* We can choose between using the implicit realignment scheme (generating
    6570                 :            :      a misaligned_move stmt) and the explicit realignment scheme (generating
    6571                 :            :      aligned loads with a REALIGN_LOAD).  There are two variants to the
    6572                 :            :      explicit realignment scheme: optimized, and unoptimized.
    6573                 :            :      We can optimize the realignment only if the step between consecutive
    6574                 :            :      vector loads is equal to the vector size.  Since the vector memory
    6575                 :            :      accesses advance in steps of VS (Vector Size) in the vectorized loop, it
    6576                 :            :      is guaranteed that the misalignment amount remains the same throughout the
    6577                 :            :      execution of the vectorized loop.  Therefore, we can create the
    6578                 :            :      "realignment token" (the permutation mask that is passed to REALIGN_LOAD)
    6579                 :            :      at the loop preheader.
    6580                 :            : 
    6581                 :            :      However, in the case of outer-loop vectorization, when vectorizing a
    6582                 :            :      memory access in the inner-loop nested within the LOOP that is now being
    6583                 :            :      vectorized, while it is guaranteed that the misalignment of the
    6584                 :            :      vectorized memory access will remain the same in different outer-loop
    6585                 :            :      iterations, it is *not* guaranteed that is will remain the same throughout
    6586                 :            :      the execution of the inner-loop.  This is because the inner-loop advances
    6587                 :            :      with the original scalar step (and not in steps of VS).  If the inner-loop
    6588                 :            :      step happens to be a multiple of VS, then the misalignment remains fixed
    6589                 :            :      and we can use the optimized realignment scheme.  For example:
    6590                 :            : 
    6591                 :            :       for (i=0; i<N; i++)
    6592                 :            :         for (j=0; j<M; j++)
    6593                 :            :           s += a[i+j];
    6594                 :            : 
    6595                 :            :      When vectorizing the i-loop in the above example, the step between
    6596                 :            :      consecutive vector loads is 1, and so the misalignment does not remain
    6597                 :            :      fixed across the execution of the inner-loop, and the realignment cannot
    6598                 :            :      be optimized (as illustrated in the following pseudo vectorized loop):
    6599                 :            : 
    6600                 :            :       for (i=0; i<N; i+=4)
    6601                 :            :         for (j=0; j<M; j++){
    6602                 :            :           vs += vp[i+j]; // misalignment of &vp[i+j] is {0,1,2,3,0,1,2,3,...}
    6603                 :            :                          // when j is {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7,...} respectively.
    6604                 :            :                          // (assuming that we start from an aligned address).
    6605                 :            :           }
    6606                 :            : 
    6607                 :            :      We therefore have to use the unoptimized realignment scheme:
    6608                 :            : 
    6609                 :            :       for (i=0; i<N; i+=4)
    6610                 :            :           for (j=k; j<M; j+=4)
    6611                 :            :           vs += vp[i+j]; // misalignment of &vp[i+j] is always k (assuming
    6612                 :            :                            // that the misalignment of the initial address is
    6613                 :            :                            // 0).
    6614                 :            : 
    6615                 :            :      The loop can then be vectorized as follows:
    6616                 :            : 
    6617                 :            :       for (k=0; k<4; k++){
    6618                 :            :         rt = get_realignment_token (&vp[k]);

    6620                 :            :           v1 = vp[i+k];

    6622                 :            :             v2 = vp[i+j+VS-1];
    6623                 :            :             va = REALIGN_LOAD <v1,v2,rt>;
    6624                 :            :             vs += va;
    6625                 :            :             v1 = v2;
    6626                 :            :           }
    6627                 :            :         }
    6628                 :            :     } */
